ce:section.ce:para:
In order to study the stability of the 2-NCQDs/ZIS/TCN/Ti photoanode system, 5 replicates were performed. As shown in Fig. 10a, the degradation efficiency basically did not change after 5 cycles, only decreased from 95.89 % to 93.61 %, which proved the excellent stability of the system. In order to further investigate the stability of 2-NCQDs/ZIS/TCN/Ti photoanode, XRD and FTIR were used to characterize 2-NCQDs/ZIS/TCN after 5 cycles. The results in Figs. 3 and 4
                         showed that the XRD and FTIR spectra of 2-NCQDs/ZIS/TCN after reaction had no obvious changes compared with that of 2-NCQDs/ZIS/TCN before reaction, which proved that the stability of 2-NCQDs/ZIS/TCN/Ti photoanode was good. The reason for the decline of the degradation efficiency might be that the undegraded RhB was adsorbed on the surface of the photoanode every cycle, which affected its light energy absorption and occupied its active sites. To be able to better verify the stability of the system, the change of the open-circuit voltage in a certain period of time was measured. As shown in Fig. 10b, the open-circuit voltage of the system was around 0.42 V and stable for a for a specific duration, which was enough to prove the stability of the system. To continue assessing optoelectronic performance of the system, the performance of the system was compared with that of similar recent studies. The maximum power density, open circuit voltage, maximum photocurrent density and degradation performance of 2-NCQDs/ZIS/TCN/Ti-CuxO/Cu PFC were higher than that of most reports (Table 1
                        ). This is enough to prove that the performance of 2-NCQDs/ZIS/TCN/Ti-CuxO/Cu system is very excellent, and the photoanode material is very promising for PFC system.
